diff:1665155613:1665155020:=39,55c39,55%0a%3c I chose to research the Mohawk language, which is spoken in northern New York, and parts of Ontario and Quebec. The Mohawk language was spoken by the Mohawk tribe, a member of the Iroquois Confederacy/the Haudenosaunee (1). Growing up in upstate New York, many of my elementary social studies classes were filled with learning about the Iroquois, who had historically been a large trading partner with the Albany colonists.%0a%3c %0a%3c The traditional stewards of the land were the Mohawks, also known as the Kanien’kehá:ka in the Mohawk language (which is called Kanien’kehá) (2). An IPA transcription of Kanien’kehá would be [kanienʔkehá], where the [á] indicates tone (5).%0a%3c %0a%3c Before the Europeans settled in America, the Mohawk society covered a lot of land, mainly settling in the Mohawk River Valley. They moved out of the valley and further north due to conflicts in the mid-1700s. In 1760, the treaty of Kahnawake was signed. In 1796, a treaty was signed between the Seven Nations of Canada (which included some groups of Mohawks) and New York. This gave them more autonomy over their land, but also restricted them to less land (1).%0a%3c %0a%3c Through my research, I couldn’t find a specific number of speakers of the language. This might be because current Mohawk society is made up of many different smaller councils and communities that reside in different reserves. I was able to find some figures for some of the communities, and it’s clear that the language is decreasing in speakers (5). There are some organizations that are working on reviving Mohawk culture, such as the Kanien’kehá:ka Onkwawén:na Raotitióhkwa Language and Cultural Center in Quebec, Canada (2). There also exist Kanien’kehá immersion programs in schools like those provided by the Kahnawà:ke Education Center (3) and the Mohawk Community of Akwesasne (4). These programs work to teach children the Mohawk language and cultural practices, and give them support and resources. In doing so, they help keep their traditions and culture alive.%0a%3c %0a%3c The non-indigenous resource that I looked at was omniglot.com (6). One key thing that I noticed was that it mentions the origins of the words “Mohawk” and “Kanien’kehá,” which I did not come across in the other sites. It says, “the native name for the Mohawk language, Kanien'keha, means 'people of the flint'. The term Mohawk comes from a name meaning 'man-eaters' used by their Algonquian enemies.” This source also says that in 2015-2016, there were around 3,000 speakers of the Mohawk language in Canada and the US. The source that I used to understand the Mohawk alphabet (5) also had audio recordings of each of the letters/sounds, while omniglot.com only had an IPA transcription of each (6). If I were to write a summary of the language based on non-indigenous sources, I definitely wouldn’t be able to focus as much on the revitalization efforts, or be able to go in depth about the rich history of the language and its culture. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.srmt-nsn.gov/history_of_tribal_government%0a%3c https://www.korkahnawake.org/about %0a%3c https://www.kecedu.ca/about/message-from-the-director-of-education %0a%3c http://www.akwesasne.ca/history-resources/about-mca/ %0a%3c https://www.firstvoices.com/explore/FV/Workspaces/Data/Kanehsat%25C3%25A0:ke/Mohawk/Kanien'k%25C3%25A9ha%2520(Mohawk)%2520Eng/learn %0a---%0a> I chose to research the Mohawk language, which is spoken in northern New York, and parts of Ontario and Quebec. The Mohawk language was spoken by the Mohawk tribe, a member of the Iroquois Confederacy/the Haudenosaunee (1). Growing up in upstate New York, many of my elementary social studies classes were filled with learning about the Iroquois, who had historically been a large trading partner with the Albany colonists.%0a> %0a> The traditional stewards of the land were the Mohawks, also known as the Kanien’kehá:ka in the Mohawk language (which is called Kanien’kehá) (2). An IPA transcription of Kanien’kehà would be [kanienʔkehá], where the [á] indicates tone (5).%0a> %0a> Before the Europeans settled in America, the Mohawk society covered a lot of land, mainly settling in the Mohawk River Valley. They moved out of the valley and further north due to conflicts in the mid-1700s. In 1760, the treaty of Kahnawake was signed. In 1796, a treaty was signed between the Seven Nations of Canada (which included some groups of Mohawks) and New York. This gave them more autonomy over their land, but also restricted them to less land (1).%0a> %0a> Through my research, I couldn’t find a specific number of speakers of the language. This might be because current Mohawk society is made up of many different smaller councils and communities that reside in different reserves. I was able to find some figures for some of the communities, and it’s clear that the language is decreasing in speakers (5). There are some organizations that are working on reviving Mohawk culture, such as the Kanien’kehá:ka Onkwawén:na Raotitióhkwa Language and Cultural Center in Quebec, Canada (2). There also exist Kanien’kehá immersion programs in schools like those provided by the Kahnawà:ke Education Center (3) and the Mohawk Community of Akwesasne (4). These programs work to teach children the Mohawk language and cultural practices, and give them support and resources. In doing so, they help keep their traditions and culture alive.%0a> %0a> The non-indigenous resource that I looked at was omniglot.com (6). One key thing that I noticed was that it mentions the origins of the words “Mohawk” and “Kanien’kehá,” which I did not come across in the other sites. It says, “the native name for the Mohawk language, Kanien'keha, means 'people of the flint'. The term Mohawk comes from a name meaning 'man-eaters' used by their Algonquian enemies.” This source also says that in 2015-2016, there were around 3,000 speakers of the Mohawk language in Canada and the US. The source that I used to understand the Mohawk alphabet (5) also had audio recordings of each of the letters/sounds, while omniglot.com only had an IPA transcription of each (6). If I were to write a summary of the language based on non-indigenous sources, I definitely wouldn’t be able to focus as much on the revitalization efforts, or be able to go in depth about the rich history of the language and its culture. %0a> %0a> %0a> Sources:%0a> https://www.srmt-nsn.gov/history_of_tribal_government%0a> https://www.korkahnawake.org/about %0a> https://www.kecedu.ca/about/message-from-the-director-of-education %0a> http://www.akwesasne.ca/history-resources/about-mca/ %0a> https://www.firstvoices.com/explore/FV/Workspaces/Data/Kanehsat%25C3%25A0:ke/Mohawk/Kanien'k%25C3%25A9ha%2520(Mohawk)%2520Eng/learn %0a
